<sect1 id="introduction">
  <title>Introduction</title>
  <para>The <application>&app;</application> application enables you to graphically browse and manipulate the contents of a git directory tree.</para>
</sect1>

<sect1 id="history">
  <title>History view</title>
		<para>By default, <application>&app;</application> starts in <guilabel>History</guilabel> view.</para>
		<figure id="gitg-main">
		  <title>&app; Window</title>
		  <screenshot>
			 <mediaobject>
				<imageobject>
				  <imagedata fileref="figures/gitgmain.png" format="PNG"/>
					 </imageobject>
				<textobject> <phrase>Shows gitg main window.</phrase>
				</textobject>
			</mediaobject>
		  </screenshot>
		</figure>
		<para><application>&app;</application> is able to display large repositories.
		For example, the linux's repository.</para>
		<figure id="gitg-large-repo">
		  <title>&app; browsing large repository</title>
		  <screenshot>
			 <mediaobject>
				<imageobject>
				  <imagedata fileref="figures/gitglinux.png" format="PNG"/>
					 </imageobject>
				<textobject> <phrase>Shows gitg browsing a large repository (the linux's one).</phrase>
				</textobject>
			</mediaobject>
		  </screenshot>
		</figure>
		<para>It can be quite annoying to browse large with many concurrent branches.
		To ease this browsing, <application>&app;</application> is able to collapse lines.</para>
		<figure id="gitg-collapse">
		  <title>&app; browsing collapsed large repository</title>
		  <screenshot>
			 <mediaobject>
				<imageobject>
				  <imagedata fileref="figures/gitglinux2.png" format="PNG"/>
					 </imageobject>
				<textobject> <phrase>Shows gitg browsing a large repository (the linux's one) but branch lines are collapsed.</phrase>
				</textobject>
			</mediaobject>
		  </screenshot>
		</figure>
</sect1>

<sect1 id="commit">
  <title>Commit view</title>
  <para><application>&app;</application> enables you to commit you work.
  In order to do this, <application>&app;</application> reuse the <application>gitk</application> user interface design.
  So, in a single view, you can browse unstaged and staged content, display the changes, edit the commit message and fire the commit.</para>
		<figure id="gitg-stage">
		  <title>Staging changes</title>
		  <screenshot>
			 <mediaobject>
				<imageobject>
				  <imagedata fileref="figures/gitgcommit.png" format="PNG"/>
					 </imageobject>
				<textobject> <phrase>Shows gitg staging changes.</phrase>
				</textobject>
			</mediaobject>
		  </screenshot>
		</figure>
		<figure id="gitg-unstage">
		  <title>Unstaging changes</title>
		  <screenshot>
			 <mediaobject>
				<imageobject>
				  <imagedata fileref="figures/gitgcommit2.png" format="PNG"/>
					 </imageobject>
				<textobject> <phrase>Shows gitg unstaging changes.</phrase>
				</textobject>
			</mediaobject>
		  </screenshot>
		</figure>
  <note><para>You can stage (or unstage) only one hunk at a time. You just have to click on the diff line starting with <guilabel>@@</guilabel> (as shown on both screenshots).</para></note>
  <note><para>While checking changes, you can modify the size of the diff context by adjusting the ruler on the right-top-corner of the diff area.</para></note>

</sect1>

